00:23:36,910 --> 00:23:39,790
Now we can see in more detail.

235
00:23:41,330 --> 00:23:46,950
It turns out we have clear oscillation processes.

236
00:23:47,900 --> 00:24:03,730
And the moment visible, if you examine more detail, that the growth of current intersects with the fall of voltage.

237
00:24:04,990 --> 00:24:11,710
This exactly is that important moment that classical electrical engineering hushes up.

238
00:24:11,710 --> 00:24:25,160
When such a phase shift of current and voltage happens — effectively it makes 90 degrees — then in our circuit there are sine oscillations.

239
00:24:26,090 --> 00:24:35,030
And this leads to these resonance processes, which throws up the voltage on the capacity ultimately.

240
00:24:35,750 --> 00:24:38,850
Now let's discuss what we got.

241
00:24:38,850 --> 00:24:50,150
So, this point, this moment, marked with dashes, when we do key closure and connect the capacity.

242
00:24:51,170 --> 00:24:58,650
At the initial moment of time we have maximum voltage potential 200 V and zero current.

243
00:24:59,270 --> 00:25:06,870
Here is our voltage curve, and here is our current curve, remember the oscillogram.

244
00:25:06,870 --> 00:25:08,830
And here is what happens.

245
00:25:08,970 --> 00:25:18,510
Closure — the voltage starts sharply striving to zero and at this same moment the current starts growing.

246
00:25:20,210 --> 00:25:30,270
But it happens that the current growth — this part — meets with the voltage at this point.

247
00:25:31,150 --> 00:25:39,750
Here is, like in a resonance circuit, a shift of current and voltage by 90 degrees or about this.

248
00:25:39,990 --> 00:25:51,550
And these moments generate at us such powerful current oscillations that distort the current charge curve.

249
00:25:52,350 --> 00:25:58,210
It goes not as logic draws us, it goes exactly by such a graph.

250
00:25:58,210 --> 00:26:03,730
This graph may depend on many factors.

251
00:26:03,950 --> 00:26:09,310
Capacitor capacity, resistance in circuit, wire lengths, inductances.

252
00:26:10,010 --> 00:26:18,570
At us here essentially all capacities and conductors present in our experiment resonate.

253
00:26:18,650 --> 00:26:22,240
Because even the smallest conductor has inductance.

254
00:26:23,240 --> 00:26:32,580
And exactly this process lets us additionally get on the capacitor a small portion of energy.

255
00:26:33,200 --> 00:26:42,760
It turns out not on all capacitors — I specially took such a capacitor that can fast-charge, a high-quality film capacitor.

256
00:26:44,040 --> 00:26:50,540
On electrolytics this phenomenon will be expressed very weakly.

257
00:26:50,540 --> 00:26:54,640
So there are many nuances here.

258
00:26:54,800 --> 00:27:01,660
And exactly on these nuances people work and make some interesting devices.

259
00:27:02,160 --> 00:27:08,640
These transient processes that classic doesn't see point-blank, for them this is a usual graph.

260
00:27:09,220 --> 00:27:17,200
They let us charge our capacity to a bigger potential than we had at the input.

261
00:27:17,200 --> 00:27:24,040
Make conclusions yourself — is there addition or not, and what this is.

262
00:27:25,440 --> 00:27:43,620
Well, as you see, respected Herkon, your teacher turned out to be simply a lazy parrot who never conducted experiments in practice, but only repeated what he learned in smart books.

263
00:27:43,620 --> 00:27:46,560
Item 2 of Herkon's question.

264
00:27:47,380 --> 00:28:03,900
In general, he checked a Wi-Fi hub power supply, and it turns out it gives stable voltage 9 V, but on more detailed examination it turned out there's pulsation 1 Hz, as I understand.

265
00:28:05,340 --> 00:28:11,580
And the essence of the question reduces to whether you can get rid of these pulsations and further use it as duty.

266
00:28:11,580 --> 00:28:15,380
Or as power supply for chips.

267
00:28:16,960 --> 00:28:25,080
This is a common problem in switching power supplies, such pulsations with various frequencies.

268
00:28:26,280 --> 00:28:39,620
You can defeat them if you apply chains at the output that serve for filtering — these are chokes and electrolytic capacitors.

269
00:28:39,620 --> 00:28:46,800
Often the manufacturer for economy purposes puts cheap capacitors that fail fast.

270
00:28:46,960 --> 00:28:52,580
Or there happen cases when places for capacitors are still provided on the board.

271
00:28:53,720 --> 00:28:59,460
For example, the developer provided installation of three capacitors, and there instead of three stands one.

272
00:29:00,220 --> 00:29:03,680
And I understand still smaller rating than needed.

273
00:29:04,420 --> 00:29:06,520
Chokes may not be at all.

274
00:29:07,680 --> 00:29:13,460
You can install additional such chains and such pulsations may be defeated.

275
00:29:13,900 --> 00:29:17,020
Pulsation 1 Hz is of course very low-frequency.

276
00:29:17,400 --> 00:29:20,340
In this case, I don't know if you'll manage to get rid of it.

277
00:29:20,540 --> 00:29:23,820
Need to search the reason from what this happens, if interesting.

278
00:29:25,220 --> 00:29:35,900
And so, if the power supply worked and then started pulsating with some frequency, then most likely the electrolytic capacities cover.

279
00:29:36,520 --> 00:29:45,560
And in most cases, with their replacement in the output path of the power supply, this problem is gotten rid of.

280
00:29:46,680 --> 00:29:47,580
Item 3.

281
00:29:48,800 --> 00:29:55,760
Since the talk went about lab block — what are and what kinds of each pluses and minuses.

282
00:29:56,140 --> 00:30:00,060
And what is good for cosa nostra, that is for FE generator building.

283
00:30:01,520 --> 00:30:09,300
When I picked a lab power supply for myself, I immediately determined that I need a high-voltage power supply.

284
00:30:10,120 --> 00:30:19,960
And when I searched their brands, I noticed that high-voltage power supplies as such, very few manufacturers make them.

285
00:30:19,960 --> 00:30:25,620
My power supply, say, the Mostech brand — it's at 300 V.

286
00:30:26,040 --> 00:30:28,880
But such power supplies are quite expensive.

287
00:30:29,300 --> 00:30:33,440
If you don't deal professionally with something, there's no sense taking them.

288
00:30:34,220 --> 00:30:45,180
Still for the reason that these our devices we deal with in the FE generator topic should launch exclusively from a battery.

289
00:30:45,180 --> 00:30:53,360
And after the battery is made own converter at the needed voltage.

290
00:30:53,940 --> 00:30:56,700
This is how this system works.

291
00:30:57,700 --> 00:31:03,560
Why better to do through launching from battery?

292
00:31:04,200 --> 00:31:08,520
Because the system gets automatically untied at us from the network.

293
00:31:09,520 --> 00:31:26,640
In all cases when we run the system from the lab power supply, it's inevitable that our device gets connected with the network through interlayer capacity in the pulse transformer winding.

294
00:31:26,640 --> 00:31:31,180
Because our device is quite high-frequency.

295
00:31:32,460 --> 00:31:42,420
And here there can be very many problems, the smallest of which is that the device will launch unstably or won't launch at all.

296
00:31:43,500 --> 00:31:54,340
And the most — I consider probably the bigger problem — will be the moment that a hit may happen directed toward the lab power supply, and it'll fail.

297
00:31:56,940 --> 00:32:02,720
For what, say, I acquired a lab power supply at 300 V.

298
00:32:02,840 --> 00:32:06,820
The thing is, it's convenient to use.

299
00:32:06,820 --> 00:32:19,720
And further, for schemes I test — on my channel there's a video about a lab power supply with voltage up to 1000 V.

300
00:32:20,180 --> 00:32:27,900
Because in some cases, for detecting specific effects in the system, you need to raise the voltage potential higher.

301
00:32:27,900 --> 00:32:40,840
At devices there's a so-called threshold when a certain potential should be supplied so processes in the system started.

302
00:32:41,880 --> 00:32:56,700
Talk about pluses and minuses here doesn't come relative to our FE generator building because the manufacturer doesn't even assume we'll use these power supplies for this.

303
00:32:57,980 --> 00:33:03,700
I can't advise here — no one made them specially for our purposes.

304
