326
00:35:56,380 --> 00:35:58,880
Question 5 from Anatoly Avarazhikhin.

327
00:36:00,120 --> 00:36:01,820
Good day, Sergey.

328
00:36:01,940 --> 00:36:10,080
In your scheme from the clip about the flyback converter with stabilized output voltage and current protection.

329
00:36:10,080 --> 00:36:20,480
At the drain of the FET transistor stands diode FR207, resistance 5.1 Ohm, and capacitor 1 nF 1000 V.

330
00:36:21,040 --> 00:36:30,880
If I correctly understand the work of this trio, then these elements are needed for restraining the energy surge from the coil at the moment of transistor turn-off.

331
00:36:30,880 --> 00:36:42,660
Role of the capacitor — absorb this surge, the resistor — prepare the capacitor to absorb the next surge, the diode — not let high potential back to the drain.

332
00:36:43,180 --> 00:36:46,260
Didn't an error creep into the arrangement of these elements?

333
00:36:47,940 --> 00:36:51,000
Now examine this scheme in more detail.

334
00:36:52,160 --> 00:36:56,200
The talk goes about this scheme and this trio.

335
00:36:57,860 --> 00:37:02,020
Capacitor, FR207 diode, and resistance.

336
00:37:02,600 --> 00:37:09,580
Here earlier in the video clip you saw 5.1 Ohm, now I use 22 Ohm here.

337
00:37:09,680 --> 00:37:12,160
You can vary this resistance here.

338
00:37:12,920 --> 00:37:17,280
No error in the arrangement of components here, this is done by me consciously.

339
00:37:17,280 --> 00:37:22,380
And I watched the oscillograms of the key work and what happens here.

340
00:37:23,460 --> 00:37:35,660
Most often you're used to see such schemes when the diode at the FET key drain connects directly to the capacitor.

341
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:40,620
And parallel to the capacitor is the resistance.

342
00:37:41,620 --> 00:37:43,800
Here the system works so.

343
00:37:43,900 --> 00:37:53,100
When key closure happens, a surge forms that's cut off by the capacitor charge.

344
00:37:54,140 --> 00:37:56,840
The surge goes through diode FR207.

345
00:37:57,920 --> 00:38:08,480
You see that one plate of the capacitor is connected to plus power and accordingly to one of the leads of the primary winding of 9 turns.

346
00:38:10,620 --> 00:38:13,900
So the amplitude of this surge is applied to it.

347
00:38:14,820 --> 00:38:21,400
When the surge amplitude reached maximum, the capacitor charges to this amplitude.

348
00:38:21,520 --> 00:38:23,100
Further its fall happens.

349
00:38:23,960 --> 00:38:31,960
And the capacitor starts discharging through the current-limiting resistance 22 Ohm on the primary winding.

350
00:38:31,960 --> 00:38:41,040
This way increasing the time of this surge that forms at us at the key drain.

351
00:38:41,420 --> 00:38:42,880
No error in this.

352
00:38:42,980 --> 00:38:45,600
You can check yourself, assembling this scheme.

353
00:38:46,220 --> 00:38:50,420
You can naturally change the location of components by your discretion.

354
00:38:50,880 --> 00:38:58,740
I consider this an optimal scheme solution for low-voltage power of a flyback converter.

